WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:13.240
So, it's been a while since I've been in FOSDAM and one of the things that I, well I usually

00:13.240 --> 00:19.360
talk about technical topics but this is really me talking about sort of using open source

00:19.360 --> 00:25.200
instead of producing it which is quite an unusual position for me to be in.

00:25.200 --> 00:33.080
I work most often in things like the Linux kernel, I also work in open source politics

00:33.080 --> 00:38.000
so I did a lot of kernel interaction with the Linux Foundation and one of those pieces

00:38.000 --> 00:43.080
of interaction was actually being a founding member of Linux Plumbers Conference which

00:43.080 --> 00:50.080
is the conference we'll actually be talking about for this presentation.

00:50.080 --> 00:54.840
Plumbers was basically founded in 2008 as an in-person conference and it's always been

00:54.840 --> 00:59.080
an in-person conference up to the pandemic years.

00:59.080 --> 01:03.880
It's actually organized somewhat similarly to FOSDAM in that it has tracks and what are

01:03.880 --> 01:05.780
called micro conferences.

01:05.780 --> 01:10.400
The micro conferences are similar to dev rooms except they're really a bit more interactive

01:10.400 --> 01:14.840
so they're really expected to do participant conversations and usually you get a cluster

01:14.840 --> 01:20.600
of people at the front talking to each other.

01:20.600 --> 01:25.960
The tracks themselves when we have them mostly tend to be presentations so very like this

01:25.960 --> 01:31.320
but the micro conferences tend to be very discussion based so if you think about trying

01:31.320 --> 01:36.080
to do that sort of hybrid and online you realize you need some sort of highly interactive video

01:36.080 --> 01:39.440
system which is what we went through.

01:39.440 --> 01:44.200
One of the good things we had for Plumbers is that the conference actually produces quite

01:44.200 --> 01:45.500
a lot of money.

01:45.500 --> 01:52.520
We have quite a lot of sponsorship so it's quite easy to pay people to do things in the

01:52.520 --> 01:57.200
conference and one of the things we paid for in 2018 was to actually make the conference

01:57.200 --> 02:02.320
live streaming for all of those who couldn't attend and also to try and put all of the

02:02.320 --> 02:08.040
videos of every presentation and every discussion we had up on the website and obviously to

02:08.040 --> 02:14.000
do that we needed to pay somebody to run AV in each of our rooms and Plumbers tends to

02:14.000 --> 02:21.520
run us about somewhere between four and eight simultaneous tracks so we needed about 16

02:21.520 --> 02:25.760
cameras to do this and about between four and eight people to stay in the room to also

02:25.760 --> 02:29.760
do it.

02:29.760 --> 02:34.200
And obviously this then included provision of cameras in the rooms and the way we set

02:34.200 --> 02:39.440
up cameras at Plumbers is slightly different from what you have here because in your setup

02:39.440 --> 02:44.360
the camera is mostly looking down at me because you think I should be the focus of attention

02:44.360 --> 02:50.000
which is true because I'm giving the talk but when you're actually trying to record

02:50.000 --> 02:55.680
an ongoing live discussion that mostly happens between people in the audience you also need

02:55.680 --> 02:58.120
the people who are live streaming to be able to see it.

02:58.120 --> 03:02.760
So one of the other fortuitous things is Plumbers is always set up with two cameras, one at

03:02.760 --> 03:07.840
the back looking down on the speaker and then one at the front looking out at the audience

03:07.840 --> 03:12.240
and the AV guys are actually responsible for switching between the front view and the back

03:12.240 --> 03:17.120
view so that when we start to get conversations within the audience the camera can actually

03:17.120 --> 03:19.840
catch them and you can watch it.

03:19.840 --> 03:24.160
And this actually turned out to be really fortuitous as well.

03:24.160 --> 03:29.080
Obviously when you try and record your conference the first thing you realize is that in a highly

03:29.080 --> 03:34.560
interactive conference most people don't use the microphone and it's really annoying for

03:34.560 --> 03:38.920
everybody on the streaming when you get a load of silence in the room.

03:38.920 --> 03:43.720
So persuading people to use microphones is one of the key things that you have to do

03:43.720 --> 03:47.280
when you start recording your conference and this is still nothing to do with trying to

03:47.280 --> 03:52.720
get it live or hybrid, this is just recording the conference.

03:52.720 --> 03:58.040
So you have to persuade all participants in the conversation to actually use a microphone

03:58.040 --> 04:03.280
and however much money your conference makes you will only have a few microphones like

04:03.280 --> 04:08.080
this one we have two microphones at the front, I have one lavalier microphone for a room

04:08.080 --> 04:11.320
that could possibly seat over a thousand people.

04:11.320 --> 04:14.760
Trying to run around with microphones when you're doing an interactive conversation is

04:14.760 --> 04:18.600
really difficult as I assume the guys with the orange t-shirts will be able to tell you

04:18.600 --> 04:21.740
over a beer after the event.

04:21.740 --> 04:27.000
The solution we took was borrowed from another conference in Paris called Kernel Recipes

04:27.000 --> 04:33.200
which are these things called catch boxes and effectively they're square plastic polystyrene

04:33.200 --> 04:38.080
blobs that have a microphone inside that you can throw from one end of a conference room

04:38.080 --> 04:42.640
to another and this gives you a way of actually getting the microphone between the participants

04:42.640 --> 04:50.660
very fast and it's definitely fun to use and they do encourage participation.

04:50.660 --> 04:56.240
So far we've had no injuries, I should actually qualify, we've actually had no serious injuries

04:56.240 --> 05:00.360
so far with people throwing microphones at each other but I assume there's always a first

05:00.360 --> 05:04.000
time.

05:04.000 --> 05:09.000
